    <weatherForecast/>
    <avalancheActivity>
      <highlights>The wind slabs are to be assessed with care and prudence.</highlights>
      <comment>As a consequence of northwesterly wind, wind slabs formed by Thursday, 26 March. The hard wind slabs are lying on a crust in particular on sunny slopes and at high altitude. These can in isolated cases be released, even by a single winter sport participant and reach medium size. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> The avalanche prone locations are to be found in particular in gullies and bowls and on wind-loaded slopes. Along the border with France the likelihood of avalanches is higher.</comment>
    </avalancheActivity>
    <snowpackStructure>
      <comment>Over a wide area wind slabs are lying on a hard crust, especially on sunny slopes in all altitude zones, and adjacent to ridgelines and in pass areas at elevated altitudes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> High altitudes shady slopes: Towards its base, the snowpack is faceted. &lt;br/> Individual weak layers exist in the centre of the snowpack especially on west, north and northeast facing slopes. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> On sunnier slopes where temperatures are less cold, the hard surface of the snowpack will gradually soften over the course of the day. &lt;br/> &lt;br/> In particular adjacent to ridgelines at high altitude snow depths vary greatly, depending on the infuence of the wind.</comment>
    </snowpackStructure>
    <travelAdvisory/>
